ce:section.ce:para:
ROS have emerged as critical agents in CDT and PDT for cancer treatment, with singlet oxygen (1O2) and ·OH being the most effective. CDT uses the Fenton reaction to convert intracellular H2O2 into ROS, particularly ·OH, facilitating targeted destruction of cancer cells. Peroxidase (POD)-like enzyme activity is vital in this process, as it catalyzes the oxidation of 3,3′,5,5′-tetramethylbenzidine (TMB) by H2O2, leading to ROS production, which underlies the efficacy of CDT. As shown in Fig. 2
                        A, a significant absorbance at 652 nm was observed and a noticeable blue color change occurs only when Ru-CDs, TMB, and H2O2 coexist. This result indicated that the Ru-CDs effectively catalyzed H2O2 to generate ROS, converting TMB to its oxidized form. In contrast, the CDs did not exhibit this catalytic activity, underscoring the critical role of Ru for POD activity. Further analysis of the POD-like activity of the Ru-CDs revealed a corresponding increase of absorbance at 652 nm with the increase of Ru-CDs ranging from 0 ∼ 100 μg/mL (Fig. S7). Steady-state kinetic studies revealed that H2O2 followed the Michaelis–Menten model under optimal conditions (Fig. 2B, C), with a maximum initial velocity (Vmax
                        ) of 3.26 × 10−6 mM/s and a Michaelis constant (Km
                        ) of 1.63 mM. A lower Km
                         value indicated greater affinity, and a higher Vmax
                         value indicated a faster reaction for Ru-CDs than for the native enzyme horseradish peroxidase or for other CDs previously reported (Table S3).
